TF_ID¶

TF-ID is what I used to make my raw data into vectors. It is kind of neat really.If you look at the printout for the categories below it will look really strange at first. But it becomes quickly apperent that each number is kind of a coordinate, using term and document frequency; Term frequency is how often it appears in the document. Document frequency is just confusing. (The number of documents containing that specific term) The TF-IDF score is frequency matrix * inverse document frequency. In the dataframe below that is just what you see. The TFIDF score is how important a word is.

Vectorization continued¶

Now for the actual project, I split my data using the traditional train, test, split.I do not include text from the test set unless I am predicting on them. But the model does not actually see them at all until that time.

Then performed matrix vectorization and NMF (Negative matrix vectorization) to transform and model the data. To begin I actually ran a whole bunch of these but they wont fit, well anywhere so I tried to keep the stuff that I thought made a bigger difference in the model error and accuracy scores. The reconstruction error is the difference between the training data and the reconstructed data. And the accuracy was.. well the accuracy score.

For the initial model the Frobenius parameter seemed to do okay, the kullback made the error astronomical and the itakura-saito is not there because it broke everything.

I was unable to really improve my model much, which leads me to believe this model is not well suited for the task. So I am now going to compare this model to some supervised learning models. The first being SVM, which is really good at classifying data. I used a combination of Tfidf and linear SVC, which all in all gave pretty decent results. I tried to startify my sample splits differently to see how they would perform. A stratification of 0.1 performed oddly okay. Same with 0.2 and 0.3. I was very surprised by this so I decided to try to use a different model type.I must not be experienced enough with SVM to tune it as well as it needs to be.

My next supervised model ended up being a decision tree classifier. I used very basic parameters, the only thing I changed was the actual split size. I used 0.10,0.20,0.30 as values for my stratification. And my results showed improvement with each iteration. Stratification does help but there is much more to model building, and hyper paramater tuning is something I hope to continue to improve upon. Some heatmaps help highlight this. As the startification amount increases so too does number of correct predicitons per category.

All in all, the supervised learning models fared much better than the unsupervised. They showed much less overfitting and performed better overall. I think that as long as I actually performed the steps correctly the SVM model should perform well even on a small amount of data, since even with large changes in sample size the actual result numbers varied very little. Which makes sense, SVMs are very good at handling data with huge amounts of features.
